connectDeleteNamespacedServiceProxy

  • connectDeleteNamespacedServiceProxy(name: string, namespace: string, path?: undefined | string, options?: object): Promise<object>
    • Defined in api/coreV1Api.ts:307

    connect DELETE requests to proxy of Service

    Parameters

    • name: string

      name of the ServiceProxyOptions

    • namespace: string

      object name and auth scope, such as for teams and projects

    • Optional path: undefined | string

      Path is the part of URLs that include service endpoints, suffixes, and parameters to use for the current proxy request to service. For example, the whole request URL is http://localhost/api/v1/namespaces/kube-system/services/elasticsearch-logging/_search?q=user:kimchy. Path is _search?q=user:kimchy.

    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

    Returns Promise<object>

connectGetNamespacedPodAttach

  • connectGetNamespacedPodAttach(name: string, namespace: string, container?: undefined | string, stderr?: undefined | false | true, stdin?: undefined | false | true, stdout?: undefined | false | true, tty?: undefined | false | true, options?: object): Promise<object>
    • Defined in api/coreV1Api.ts:643

    connect GET requests to attach of Pod

    Parameters

    • name: string

      name of the PodAttachOptions

    • namespace: string

      object name and auth scope, such as for teams and projects

    • Optional container: undefined | string

      The container in which to execute the command. Defaults to only container if there is only one container in the pod.

    • Optional stderr: undefined | false | true

      Stderr if true indicates that stderr is to be redirected for the attach call. Defaults to true.

    • Optional stdin: undefined | false | true

      Stdin if true, redirects the standard input stream of the pod for this call. Defaults to false.

    • Optional stdout: undefined | false | true

      Stdout if true indicates that stdout is to be redirected for the attach call. Defaults to true.

    • Optional tty: undefined | false | true

      TTY if true indicates that a tty will be allocated for the attach call. This is passed through the container runtime so the tty is allocated on the worker node by the container runtime. Defaults to false.

    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

    Returns Promise<object>

connectGetNamespacedPodExec

  • connectGetNamespacedPodExec(name: string, namespace: string, command?: undefined | string, container?: undefined | string, stderr?: undefined | false | true, stdin?: undefined | false | true, stdout?: undefined | false | true, tty?: undefined | false | true, options?: object): Promise<object>
    • Defined in api/coreV1Api.ts:747

    connect GET requests to exec of Pod

    Parameters

    • name: string

      name of the PodExecOptions

    • namespace: string

      object name and auth scope, such as for teams and projects

    • Optional command: undefined | string

      Command is the remote command to execute. argv array. Not executed within a shell.

    • Optional container: undefined | string

      Container in which to execute the command. Defaults to only container if there is only one container in the pod.

    • Optional stderr: undefined | false | true

      Redirect the standard error stream of the pod for this call. Defaults to true.

    • Optional stdin: undefined | false | true

      Redirect the standard input stream of the pod for this call. Defaults to false.

    • Optional stdout: undefined | false | true

      Redirect the standard output stream of the pod for this call. Defaults to true.

    • Optional tty: undefined | false | true

      TTY if true indicates that a tty will be allocated for the exec call. Defaults to false.

    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

    Returns Promise<object>

  • connectPostNamespacedPodAttach(name: string, namespace: string, container?: undefined | string, stderr?: undefined | false | true, stdin?: undefined | false | true, stdout?: undefined | false | true, tty?: undefined | false | true, options?: object): Promise<object>
    • Defined in api/coreV1Api.ts:2957

    connect POST requests to attach of Pod

    Parameters

    • name: string

      name of the PodAttachOptions

    • namespace: string

      object name and auth scope, such as for teams and projects

    • Optional container: undefined | string

      The container in which to execute the command. Defaults to only container if there is only one container in the pod.

    • Optional stderr: undefined | false | true

      Stderr if true indicates that stderr is to be redirected for the attach call. Defaults to true.

    • Optional stdin: undefined | false | true

      Stdin if true, redirects the standard input stream of the pod for this call. Defaults to false.

    • Optional stdout: undefined | false | true

      Stdout if true indicates that stdout is to be redirected for the attach call. Defaults to true.

    • Optional tty: undefined | false | true

      TTY if true indicates that a tty will be allocated for the attach call. This is passed through the container runtime so the tty is allocated on the worker node by the container runtime. Defaults to false.

    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

    Returns Promise<object>

      When present, indicates that modifications should not be persisted. An invalid or unrecognized dryRun directive will result in an error response and no further processing of the request. Valid values are: - All: all dry run stages will be processed

    • Optional fieldManager: undefined | string

      fieldManager is a name associated with the actor or entity that is making these changes. The value must be less than or 128 characters long, and only contain printable characters, as defined by https://golang.org/pkg/unicode/#IsPrint.

    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}

deleteCollectionNamespacedConfigMap

  • deleteCollectionNamespacedConfigMap(namespace: string, pretty?: undefined | string, allowWatchBookmarks?: undefined | false | true, _continue?: undefined | string, dryRun?: undefined | string, fieldSelector?: undefined | string, gracePeriodSeconds?: undefined | number, labelSelector?: undefined | string, limit?: undefined | number, orphanDependents?: undefined | false | true, propagationPolicy?: undefined | string, resourceVersion?: undefined | string, timeoutSeconds?: undefined | number, watch?: undefined | false | true, body?: V1DeleteOptions, options?: object): Promise<object>
    • Defined in api/coreV1Api.ts:5936

    delete collection of ConfigMap

    Parameters

    • namespace: string

      object name and auth scope, such as for teams and projects

    • Optional pretty: undefined | string

      If &#39;true&#39;, then the output is pretty printed.

    • Optional allowWatchBookmarks: undefined | false | true

      allowWatchBookmarks requests watch events with type &quot;BOOKMARK&quot;. Servers that do not implement bookmarks may ignore this flag and bookmarks are sent at the server&#39;s discretion. Clients should not assume bookmarks are returned at any specific interval, nor may they assume the server will send any BOOKMARK event during a session. If this is not a watch, this field is ignored. If the feature gate WatchBookmarks is not enabled in apiserver, this field is ignored. This field is alpha and can be changed or removed without notice.

    • Optional _continue: undefined | string

      The continue option should be set when retrieving more results from the server. Since this value is server defined, clients may only use the continue value from a previous query result with identical query parameters (except for the value of continue) and the server may reject a continue value it does not recognize. If the specified continue value is no longer valid whether due to expiration (generally five to fifteen minutes) or a configuration change on the server, the server will respond with a 410 ResourceExpired error together with a continue token. If the client needs a consistent list, it must restart their list without the continue field. Otherwise, the client may send another list request with the token received with the 410 error, the server will respond with a list starting from the next key, but from the latest snapshot, which is inconsistent from the previous list results - objects that are created, modified, or deleted after the first list request will be included in the response, as long as their keys are after the &quot;next key&quot;. This field is not supported when watch is true. Clients may start a watch from the last resourceVersion value returned by the server and not miss any modifications.

    • Optional dryRun: undefined | string

      When present, indicates that modifications should not be persisted. An invalid or unrecognized dryRun directive will result in an error response and no further processing of the request. Valid values are: - All: all dry run stages will be processed

    • Optional fieldSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their fields. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional gracePeriodSeconds: undefined | number

      The duration in seconds before the object should be deleted. Value must be non-negative integer. The value zero indicates delete immediately. If this value is nil, the default grace period for the specified type will be used. Defaults to a per object value if not specified. zero means delete immediately.

    • Optional labelSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their labels. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional limit: undefined | number

      limit is a maximum number of responses to return for a list call. If more items exist, the server will set the `continue` field on the list metadata to a value that can be used with the same initial query to retrieve the next set of results. Setting a limit may return fewer than the requested amount of items (up to zero items) in the event all requested objects are filtered out and clients should only use the presence of the continue field to determine whether more results are available. Servers may choose not to support the limit argument and will return all of the available results. If limit is specified and the continue field is empty, clients may assume that no more results are available. This field is not supported if watch is true. The server guarantees that the objects returned when using continue will be identical to issuing a single list call without a limit - that is, no objects created, modified, or deleted after the first request is issued will be included in any subsequent continued requests. This is sometimes referred to as a consistent snapshot, and ensures that a client that is using limit to receive smaller chunks of a very large result can ensure they see all possible objects. If objects are updated during a chunked list the version of the object that was present at the time the first list result was calculated is returned.

    • Optional orphanDependents: undefined | false | true

      Deprecated: please use the PropagationPolicy, this field will be deprecated in 1.7. Should the dependent objects be orphaned. If true/false, the &quot;orphan&quot; finalizer will be added to/removed from the object&#39;s finalizers list. Either this field or PropagationPolicy may be set, but not both.

    • Optional propagationPolicy: undefined | string

      Whether and how garbage collection will be performed. Either this field or OrphanDependents may be set, but not both. The default policy is decided by the existing finalizer set in the metadata.finalizers and the resource-specific default policy. Acceptable values are: &#39;Orphan&#39; - orphan the dependents; &#39;Background&#39; - allow the garbage collector to delete the dependents in the background; &#39;Foreground&#39; - a cascading policy that deletes all dependents in the foreground.

    • Optional resourceVersion: undefined | string

      When specified with a watch call, shows changes that occur after that particular version of a resource. Defaults to changes from the beginning of history. When specified for list: - if unset, then the result is returned from remote storage based on quorum-read flag; - if it&#39;s 0, then we simply return what we currently have in cache, no guarantee; - if set to non zero, then the result is at least as fresh as given rv.

    • Optional timeoutSeconds: undefined | number

      Timeout for the list/watch call. This limits the duration of the call, regardless of any activity or inactivity.

    • Optional watch: undefined | false | true

      Watch for changes to the described resources and return them as a stream of add, update, and remove notifications. Specify resourceVersion.

    • Optional body: V1DeleteOptions
    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

    Returns Promise<object>

      Deprecated: please use the PropagationPolicy, this field will be deprecated in 1.7. Should the dependent objects be orphaned. If true/false, the &quot;orphan&quot; finalizer will be added to/removed from the object&#39;s finalizers list. Either this field or PropagationPolicy may be set, but not both.

    • Optional propagationPolicy: undefined | string

      Whether and how garbage collection will be performed. Either this field or OrphanDependents may be set, but not both. The default policy is decided by the existing finalizer set in the metadata.finalizers and the resource-specific default policy. Acceptable values are: &#39;Orphan&#39; - orphan the dependents; &#39;Background&#39; - allow the garbage collector to delete the dependents in the background; &#39;Foreground&#39; - a cascading policy that deletes all dependents in the foreground.

    • Optional resourceVersion: undefined | string

      When specified with a watch call, shows changes that occur after that particular version of a resource. Defaults to changes from the beginning of history. When specified for list: - if unset, then the result is returned from remote storage based on quorum-read flag; - if it&#39;s 0, then we simply return what we currently have in cache, no guarantee; - if set to non zero, then the result is at least as fresh as given rv.

    • Optional timeoutSeconds: undefined | number

      Timeout for the list/watch call. This limits the duration of the call, regardless of any activity or inactivity.

    • Optional watch: undefined | false | true

      Watch for changes to the described resources and return them as a stream of add, update, and remove notifications. Specify resourceVersion.

    • Optional body: V1DeleteOptions
    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

    Returns Promise<object>

    Parameters

    • namespace: string

      object name and auth scope, such as for teams and projects

    • Optional pretty: undefined | string

      If &#39;true&#39;, then the output is pretty printed.

    • Optional allowWatchBookmarks: undefined | false | true

      allowWatchBookmarks requests watch events with type &quot;BOOKMARK&quot;. Servers that do not implement bookmarks may ignore this flag and bookmarks are sent at the server&#39;s discretion. Clients should not assume bookmarks are returned at any specific interval, nor may they assume the server will send any BOOKMARK event during a session. If this is not a watch, this field is ignored. If the feature gate WatchBookmarks is not enabled in apiserver, this field is ignored. This field is alpha and can be changed or removed without notice.

    • Optional _continue: undefined | string

      The continue option should be set when retrieving more results from the server. Since this value is server defined, clients may only use the continue value from a previous query result with identical query parameters (except for the value of continue) and the server may reject a continue value it does not recognize. If the specified continue value is no longer valid whether due to expiration (generally five to fifteen minutes) or a configuration change on the server, the server will respond with a 410 ResourceExpired error together with a continue token. If the client needs a consistent list, it must restart their list without the continue field. Otherwise, the client may send another list request with the token received with the 410 error, the server will respond with a list starting from the next key, but from the latest snapshot, which is inconsistent from the previous list results - objects that are created, modified, or deleted after the first list request will be included in the response, as long as their keys are after the &quot;next key&quot;. This field is not supported when watch is true. Clients may start a watch from the last resourceVersion value returned by the server and not miss any modifications.

    • Optional dryRun: undefined | string

      When present, indicates that modifications should not be persisted. An invalid or unrecognized dryRun directive will result in an error response and no further processing of the request. Valid values are: - All: all dry run stages will be processed

    • Optional fieldSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their fields. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional gracePeriodSeconds: undefined | number

      The duration in seconds before the object should be deleted. Value must be non-negative integer. The value zero indicates delete immediately. If this value is nil, the default grace period for the specified type will be used. Defaults to a per object value if not specified. zero means delete immediately.

    • Optional labelSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their labels. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional limit: undefined | number

      limit is a maximum number of responses to return for a list call. If more items exist, the server will set the `continue` field on the list metadata to a value that can be used with the same initial query to retrieve the next set of results. Setting a limit may return fewer than the requested amount of items (up to zero items) in the event all requested objects are filtered out and clients should only use the presence of the continue field to determine whether more results are available. Servers may choose not to support the limit argument and will return all of the available results. If limit is specified and the continue field is empty, clients may assume that no more results are available. This field is not supported if watch is true. The server guarantees that the objects returned when using continue will be identical to issuing a single list call without a limit - that is, no objects created, modified, or deleted after the first request is issued will be included in any subsequent continued requests. This is sometimes referred to as a consistent snapshot, and ensures that a client that is using limit to receive smaller chunks of a very large result can ensure they see all possible objects. If objects are updated during a chunked list the version of the object that was present at the time the first list result was calculated is returned.

    • Optional orphanDependents: undefined | false | true

      Deprecated: please use the PropagationPolicy, this field will be deprecated in 1.7. Should the dependent objects be orphaned. If true/false, the &quot;orphan&quot; finalizer will be added to/removed from the object&#39;s finalizers list. Either this field or PropagationPolicy may be set, but not both.

    • Optional propagationPolicy: undefined | string

      Whether and how garbage collection will be performed. Either this field or OrphanDependents may be set, but not both. The default policy is decided by the existing finalizer set in the metadata.finalizers and the resource-specific default policy. Acceptable values are: &#39;Orphan&#39; - orphan the dependents; &#39;Background&#39; - allow the garbage collector to delete the dependents in the background; &#39;Foreground&#39; - a cascading policy that deletes all dependents in the foreground.

    • Optional resourceVersion: undefined | string

      When specified with a watch call, shows changes that occur after that particular version of a resource. Defaults to changes from the beginning of history. When specified for list: - if unset, then the result is returned from remote storage based on quorum-read flag; - if it&#39;s 0, then we simply return what we currently have in cache, no guarantee; - if set to non zero, then the result is at least as fresh as given rv.

    • Optional timeoutSeconds: undefined | number

      Timeout for the list/watch call. This limits the duration of the call, regardless of any activity or inactivity.

    • Optional watch: undefined | false | true

      Watch for changes to the described resources and return them as a stream of add, update, and remove notifications. Specify resourceVersion.

    • Optional body: V1DeleteOptions
    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

    Returns Promise<object>

deleteCollectionNamespacedSecret

  • deleteCollectionNamespacedSecret(namespace: string, pretty?: undefined | string, allowWatchBookmarks?: undefined | false | true, _continue?: undefined | string, dryRun?: undefined | string, fieldSelector?: undefined | string, gracePeriodSeconds?: undefined | number, labelSelector?: undefined | string, limit?: undefined | number, orphanDependents?: undefined | false | true, propagationPolicy?: undefined | string, resourceVersion?: undefined | string, timeoutSeconds?: undefined | number, watch?: undefined | false | true, body?: V1DeleteOptions, options?: object): Promise<object>
    • Defined in api/coreV1Api.ts:7178

    delete collection of Secret

    Parameters

    • namespace: string

      object name and auth scope, such as for teams and projects

    • Optional pretty: undefined | string

      If &#39;true&#39;, then the output is pretty printed.

    • Optional allowWatchBookmarks: undefined | false | true

      allowWatchBookmarks requests watch events with type &quot;BOOKMARK&quot;. Servers that do not implement bookmarks may ignore this flag and bookmarks are sent at the server&#39;s discretion. Clients should not assume bookmarks are returned at any specific interval, nor may they assume the server will send any BOOKMARK event during a session. If this is not a watch, this field is ignored. If the feature gate WatchBookmarks is not enabled in apiserver, this field is ignored. This field is alpha and can be changed or removed without notice.

    • Optional _continue: undefined | string

      The continue option should be set when retrieving more results from the server. Since this value is server defined, clients may only use the continue value from a previous query result with identical query parameters (except for the value of continue) and the server may reject a continue value it does not recognize. If the specified continue value is no longer valid whether due to expiration (generally five to fifteen minutes) or a configuration change on the server, the server will respond with a 410 ResourceExpired error together with a continue token. If the client needs a consistent list, it must restart their list without the continue field. Otherwise, the client may send another list request with the token received with the 410 error, the server will respond with a list starting from the next key, but from the latest snapshot, which is inconsistent from the previous list results - objects that are created, modified, or deleted after the first list request will be included in the response, as long as their keys are after the &quot;next key&quot;. This field is not supported when watch is true. Clients may start a watch from the last resourceVersion value returned by the server and not miss any modifications.

    • Optional dryRun: undefined | string

      When present, indicates that modifications should not be persisted. An invalid or unrecognized dryRun directive will result in an error response and no further processing of the request. Valid values are: - All: all dry run stages will be processed

    • Optional fieldSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their fields. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional gracePeriodSeconds: undefined | number

      The duration in seconds before the object should be deleted. Value must be non-negative integer. The value zero indicates delete immediately. If this value is nil, the default grace period for the specified type will be used. Defaults to a per object value if not specified. zero means delete immediately.

    • Optional labelSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their labels. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional limit: undefined | number

      limit is a maximum number of responses to return for a list call. If more items exist, the server will set the `continue` field on the list metadata to a value that can be used with the same initial query to retrieve the next set of results. Setting a limit may return fewer than the requested amount of items (up to zero items) in the event all requested objects are filtered out and clients should only use the presence of the continue field to determine whether more results are available. Servers may choose not to support the limit argument and will return all of the available results. If limit is specified and the continue field is empty, clients may assume that no more results are available. This field is not supported if watch is true. The server guarantees that the objects returned when using continue will be identical to issuing a single list call without a limit - that is, no objects created, modified, or deleted after the first request is issued will be included in any subsequent continued requests. This is sometimes referred to as a consistent snapshot, and ensures that a client that is using limit to receive smaller chunks of a very large result can ensure they see all possible objects. If objects are updated during a chunked list the version of the object that was present at the time the first list result was calculated is returned.

    • Optional orphanDependents: undefined | false | true

      Deprecated: please use the PropagationPolicy, this field will be deprecated in 1.7. Should the dependent objects be orphaned. If true/false, the &quot;orphan&quot; finalizer will be added to/removed from the object&#39;s finalizers list. Either this field or PropagationPolicy may be set, but not both.

    • Optional propagationPolicy: undefined | string

      Whether and how garbage collection will be performed. Either this field or OrphanDependents may be set, but not both. The default policy is decided by the existing finalizer set in the metadata.finalizers and the resource-specific default policy. Acceptable values are: &#39;Orphan&#39; - orphan the dependents; &#39;Background&#39; - allow the garbage collector to delete the dependents in the background; &#39;Foreground&#39; - a cascading policy that deletes all dependents in the foreground.

    • Optional resourceVersion: undefined | string

      When specified with a watch call, shows changes that occur after that particular version of a resource. Defaults to changes from the beginning of history. When specified for list: - if unset, then the result is returned from remote storage based on quorum-read flag; - if it&#39;s 0, then we simply return what we currently have in cache, no guarantee; - if set to non zero, then the result is at least as fresh as given rv.

    • Optional timeoutSeconds: undefined | number

      Timeout for the list/watch call. This limits the duration of the call, regardless of any activity or inactivity.

    • Optional watch: undefined | false | true

      Watch for changes to the described resources and return them as a stream of add, update, and remove notifications. Specify resourceVersion.

    • Optional body: V1DeleteOptions
    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

      Whether and how garbage collection will be performed. Either this field or OrphanDependents may be set, but not both. The default policy is decided by the existing finalizer set in the metadata.finalizers and the resource-specific default policy. Acceptable values are: &#39;Orphan&#39; - orphan the dependents; &#39;Background&#39; - allow the garbage collector to delete the dependents in the background; &#39;Foreground&#39; - a cascading policy that deletes all dependents in the foreground.

    • Optional body: V1DeleteOptions
    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

listComponentStatus

  • listComponentStatus(allowWatchBookmarks?: undefined | false | true, _continue?: undefined | string, fieldSelector?: undefined | string, labelSelector?: undefined | string, limit?: undefined | number, pretty?: undefined | string, resourceVersion?: undefined | string, timeoutSeconds?: undefined | number, watch?: undefined | false | true, options?: object): Promise<object>
    • Defined in api/coreV1Api.ts:9328

    list objects of kind ComponentStatus

    Parameters

    • Optional allowWatchBookmarks: undefined | false | true

      allowWatchBookmarks requests watch events with type &quot;BOOKMARK&quot;. Servers that do not implement bookmarks may ignore this flag and bookmarks are sent at the server&#39;s discretion. Clients should not assume bookmarks are returned at any specific interval, nor may they assume the server will send any BOOKMARK event during a session. If this is not a watch, this field is ignored. If the feature gate WatchBookmarks is not enabled in apiserver, this field is ignored. This field is alpha and can be changed or removed without notice.

    • Optional _continue: undefined | string

      The continue option should be set when retrieving more results from the server. Since this value is server defined, clients may only use the continue value from a previous query result with identical query parameters (except for the value of continue) and the server may reject a continue value it does not recognize. If the specified continue value is no longer valid whether due to expiration (generally five to fifteen minutes) or a configuration change on the server, the server will respond with a 410 ResourceExpired error together with a continue token. If the client needs a consistent list, it must restart their list without the continue field. Otherwise, the client may send another list request with the token received with the 410 error, the server will respond with a list starting from the next key, but from the latest snapshot, which is inconsistent from the previous list results - objects that are created, modified, or deleted after the first list request will be included in the response, as long as their keys are after the &quot;next key&quot;. This field is not supported when watch is true. Clients may start a watch from the last resourceVersion value returned by the server and not miss any modifications.

    • Optional fieldSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their fields. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional labelSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their labels. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional limit: undefined | number

      limit is a maximum number of responses to return for a list call. If more items exist, the server will set the `continue` field on the list metadata to a value that can be used with the same initial query to retrieve the next set of results. Setting a limit may return fewer than the requested amount of items (up to zero items) in the event all requested objects are filtered out and clients should only use the presence of the continue field to determine whether more results are available. Servers may choose not to support the limit argument and will return all of the available results. If limit is specified and the continue field is empty, clients may assume that no more results are available. This field is not supported if watch is true. The server guarantees that the objects returned when using continue will be identical to issuing a single list call without a limit - that is, no objects created, modified, or deleted after the first request is issued will be included in any subsequent continued requests. This is sometimes referred to as a consistent snapshot, and ensures that a client that is using limit to receive smaller chunks of a very large result can ensure they see all possible objects. If objects are updated during a chunked list the version of the object that was present at the time the first list result was calculated is returned.

    • Optional pretty: undefined | string

      If &#39;true&#39;, then the output is pretty printed.

    • Optional resourceVersion: undefined | string

      When specified with a watch call, shows changes that occur after that particular version of a resource. Defaults to changes from the beginning of history. When specified for list: - if unset, then the result is returned from remote storage based on quorum-read flag; - if it&#39;s 0, then we simply return what we currently have in cache, no guarantee; - if set to non zero, then the result is at least as fresh as given rv.

    • Optional timeoutSeconds: undefined | number

      Timeout for the list/watch call. This limits the duration of the call, regardless of any activity or inactivity.

    • Optional watch: undefined | false | true

      Watch for changes to the described resources and return them as a stream of add, update, and remove notifications. Specify resourceVersion.

    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

    Returns Promise<object>

listConfigMapForAllNamespaces

  • listConfigMapForAllNamespaces(allowWatchBookmarks?: undefined | false | true, _continue?: undefined | string, fieldSelector?: undefined | string, labelSelector?: undefined | string, limit?: undefined | number, pretty?: undefined | string, resourceVersion?: undefined | string, timeoutSeconds?: undefined | number, watch?: undefined | false | true, options?: object): Promise<object>
    • Defined in api/coreV1Api.ts:9437

    list or watch objects of kind ConfigMap

    Parameters

    • Optional allowWatchBookmarks: undefined | false | true

      allowWatchBookmarks requests watch events with type &quot;BOOKMARK&quot;. Servers that do not implement bookmarks may ignore this flag and bookmarks are sent at the server&#39;s discretion. Clients should not assume bookmarks are returned at any specific interval, nor may they assume the server will send any BOOKMARK event during a session. If this is not a watch, this field is ignored. If the feature gate WatchBookmarks is not enabled in apiserver, this field is ignored. This field is alpha and can be changed or removed without notice.

    • Optional _continue: undefined | string

      The continue option should be set when retrieving more results from the server. Since this value is server defined, clients may only use the continue value from a previous query result with identical query parameters (except for the value of continue) and the server may reject a continue value it does not recognize. If the specified continue value is no longer valid whether due to expiration (generally five to fifteen minutes) or a configuration change on the server, the server will respond with a 410 ResourceExpired error together with a continue token. If the client needs a consistent list, it must restart their list without the continue field. Otherwise, the client may send another list request with the token received with the 410 error, the server will respond with a list starting from the next key, but from the latest snapshot, which is inconsistent from the previous list results - objects that are created, modified, or deleted after the first list request will be included in the response, as long as their keys are after the &quot;next key&quot;. This field is not supported when watch is true. Clients may start a watch from the last resourceVersion value returned by the server and not miss any modifications.

    • Optional fieldSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their fields. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional labelSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their labels. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional limit: undefined | number

      limit is a maximum number of responses to return for a list call. If more items exist, the server will set the `continue` field on the list metadata to a value that can be used with the same initial query to retrieve the next set of results. Setting a limit may return fewer than the requested amount of items (up to zero items) in the event all requested objects are filtered out and clients should only use the presence of the continue field to determine whether more results are available. Servers may choose not to support the limit argument and will return all of the available results. If limit is specified and the continue field is empty, clients may assume that no more results are available. This field is not supported if watch is true. The server guarantees that the objects returned when using continue will be identical to issuing a single list call without a limit - that is, no objects created, modified, or deleted after the first request is issued will be included in any subsequent continued requests. This is sometimes referred to as a consistent snapshot, and ensures that a client that is using limit to receive smaller chunks of a very large result can ensure they see all possible objects. If objects are updated during a chunked list the version of the object that was present at the time the first list result was calculated is returned.

    • Optional pretty: undefined | string

      If &#39;true&#39;, then the output is pretty printed.

    • Optional resourceVersion: undefined | string

      When specified with a watch call, shows changes that occur after that particular version of a resource. Defaults to changes from the beginning of history. When specified for list: - if unset, then the result is returned from remote storage based on quorum-read flag; - if it&#39;s 0, then we simply return what we currently have in cache, no guarantee; - if set to non zero, then the result is at least as fresh as given rv.

    • Optional timeoutSeconds: undefined | number

      Timeout for the list/watch call. This limits the duration of the call, regardless of any activity or inactivity.

    • Optional watch: undefined | false | true

      Watch for changes to the described resources and return them as a stream of add, update, and remove notifications. Specify resourceVersion.

    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}

If objects are updated during a chunked list the version of the object that was present at the time the first list result was calculated is returned.

    • Optional resourceVersion: undefined | string

      When specified with a watch call, shows changes that occur after that particular version of a resource. Defaults to changes from the beginning of history. When specified for list: - if unset, then the result is returned from remote storage based on quorum-read flag; - if it&#39;s 0, then we simply return what we currently have in cache, no guarantee; - if set to non zero, then the result is at least as fresh as given rv.

    • Optional timeoutSeconds: undefined | number

      Timeout for the list/watch call. This limits the duration of the call, regardless of any activity or inactivity.

    • Optional watch: undefined | false | true

      Watch for changes to the described resources and return them as a stream of add, update, and remove notifications. Specify resourceVersion.

    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

    Returns Promise<object>

listNamespacedEvent

  • listNamespacedEvent(namespace: string, pretty?: undefined | string, allowWatchBookmarks?: undefined | false | true, _continue?: undefined | string, fieldSelector?: undefined | string, labelSelector?: undefined | string, limit?: undefined | number, resourceVersion?: undefined | string, timeoutSeconds?: undefined | number, watch?: undefined | false | true, options?: object): Promise<object>
    • Defined in api/coreV1Api.ts:10215

    list or watch objects of kind Event

    Parameters

    • namespace: string

      object name and auth scope, such as for teams and projects

    • Optional pretty: undefined | string

      If &#39;true&#39;, then the output is pretty printed.

    • Optional allowWatchBookmarks: undefined | false | true

      allowWatchBookmarks requests watch events with type &quot;BOOKMARK&quot;. Servers that do not implement bookmarks may ignore this flag and bookmarks are sent at the server&#39;s discretion. Clients should not assume bookmarks are returned at any specific interval, nor may they assume the server will send any BOOKMARK event during a session. If this is not a watch, this field is ignored. If the feature gate WatchBookmarks is not enabled in apiserver, this field is ignored. This field is alpha and can be changed or removed without notice.

    • Optional _continue: undefined | string

      The continue option should be set when retrieving more results from the server. Since this value is server defined, clients may only use the continue value from a previous query result with identical query parameters (except for the value of continue) and the server may reject a continue value it does not recognize. If the specified continue value is no longer valid whether due to expiration (generally five to fifteen minutes) or a configuration change on the server, the server will respond with a 410 ResourceExpired error together with a continue token. If the client needs a consistent list, it must restart their list without the continue field. Otherwise, the client may send another list request with the token received with the 410 error, the server will respond with a list starting from the next key, but from the latest snapshot, which is inconsistent from the previous list results - objects that are created, modified, or deleted after the first list request will be included in the response, as long as their keys are after the &quot;next key&quot;. This field is not supported when watch is true. Clients may start a watch from the last resourceVersion value returned by the server and not miss any modifications.

    • Optional fieldSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their fields. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional labelSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their labels. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional limit: undefined | number

      limit is a maximum number of responses to return for a list call. If more items exist, the server will set the `continue` field on the list metadata to a value that can be used with the same initial query to retrieve the next set of results. Setting a limit may return fewer than the requested amount of items (up to zero items) in the event all requested objects are filtered out and clients should only use the presence of the continue field to determine whether more results are available. Servers may choose not to support the limit argument and will return all of the available results. If limit is specified and the continue field is empty, clients may assume that no more results are available. This field is not supported if watch is true. The server guarantees that the objects returned when using continue will be identical to issuing a single list call without a limit - that is, no objects created, modified, or deleted after the first request is issued will be included in any subsequent continued requests. This is sometimes referred to as a consistent snapshot, and ensures that a client that is using limit to receive smaller chunks of a very large result can ensure they see all possible objects. If objects are updated during a chunked list the version of the object that was present at the time the first list result was calculated is returned.

    • Optional resourceVersion: undefined | string

      When specified with a watch call, shows changes that occur after that particular version of a resource. Defaults to changes from the beginning of history. When specified for list: - if unset, then the result is returned from remote storage based on quorum-read flag; - if it&#39;s 0, then we simply return what we currently have in cache, no guarantee; - if set to non zero, then the result is at least as fresh as given rv.

    • Optional timeoutSeconds: undefined | number

      Timeout for the list/watch call. This limits the duration of the call, regardless of any activity or inactivity.

    • Optional watch: undefined | false | true

      Watch for changes to the described resources and return them as a stream of add, update, and remove notifications. Specify resourceVersion.

    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

The server guarantees that the objects returned when using continue will be identical to issuing a single list call without a limit - that is, no objects created, modified, or deleted after the first request is issued will be included in any subsequent continued requests. This is sometimes referred to as a consistent snapshot, and ensures that a client that is using limit to receive smaller chunks of a very large result can ensure they see all possible objects. If objects are updated during a chunked list the version of the object that was present at the time the first list result was calculated is returned.

    • Optional resourceVersion: undefined | string

      When specified with a watch call, shows changes that occur after that particular version of a resource. Defaults to changes from the beginning of history. When specified for list: - if unset, then the result is returned from remote storage based on quorum-read flag; - if it&#39;s 0, then we simply return what we currently have in cache, no guarantee; - if set to non zero, then the result is at least as fresh as given rv.

    • Optional timeoutSeconds: undefined | number

      Timeout for the list/watch call. This limits the duration of the call, regardless of any activity or inactivity.

    • Optional watch: undefined | false | true

      Watch for changes to the described resources and return them as a stream of add, update, and remove notifications. Specify resourceVersion.

    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

    Returns Promise<object>

    Parameters

      object name and auth scope, such as for teams and projects

    • Optional pretty: undefined | string

      If &#39;true&#39;, then the output is pretty printed.

    • Optional allowWatchBookmarks: undefined | false | true

      allowWatchBookmarks requests watch events with type &quot;BOOKMARK&quot;. Servers that do not implement bookmarks may ignore this flag and bookmarks are sent at the server&#39;s discretion. Clients should not assume bookmarks are returned at any specific interval, nor may they assume the server will send any BOOKMARK event during a session. If this is not a watch, this field is ignored. If the feature gate WatchBookmarks is not enabled in apiserver, this field is ignored. This field is alpha and can be changed or removed without notice.

    • Optional _continue: undefined | string

      The continue option should be set when retrieving more results from the server. Since this value is server defined, clients may only use the continue value from a previous query result with identical query parameters (except for the value of continue) and the server may reject a continue value it does not recognize. If the specified continue value is no longer valid whether due to expiration (generally five to fifteen minutes) or a configuration change on the server, the server will respond with a 410 ResourceExpired error together with a continue token. If the client needs a consistent list, it must restart their list without the continue field. Otherwise, the client may send another list request with the token received with the 410 error, the server will respond with a list starting from the next key, but from the latest snapshot, which is inconsistent from the previous list results - objects that are created, modified, or deleted after the first list request will be included in the response, as long as their keys are after the &quot;next key&quot;. This field is not supported when watch is true. Clients may start a watch from the last resourceVersion value returned by the server and not miss any modifications.

    • Optional fieldSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their fields. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional labelSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their labels. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional limit: undefined | number

      limit is a maximum number of responses to return for a list call. If more items exist, the server will set the `continue` field on the list metadata to a value that can be used with the same initial query to retrieve the next set of results. Setting a limit may return fewer than the requested amount of items (up to zero items) in the event all requested objects are filtered out and clients should only use the presence of the continue field to determine whether more results are available. Servers may choose not to support the limit argument and will return all of the available results. If limit is specified and the continue field is empty, clients may assume that no more results are available. This field is not supported if watch is true. If objects are updated during a chunked list the version of the object that was present at the time the first list result was calculated is returned.

    • Optional resourceVersion: undefined | string

      When specified with a watch call, shows changes that occur after that particular version of a resource. Defaults to changes from the beginning of history. This is sometimes referred to as a consistent snapshot, and ensures that a client that is using limit to receive smaller chunks of a very large result can ensure they see all possible objects. If objects are updated during a chunked list the version of the object that was present at the time the first list result was calculated is returned.

    • Optional pretty: undefined | string

      If &#39;true&#39;, then the output is pretty printed.

    • Optional resourceVersion: undefined | string

      When specified with a watch call, shows changes that occur after that particular version of a resource. Defaults to changes from the beginning of history. When specified for list: - if unset, then the result is returned from remote storage based on quorum-read flag; - if it&#39;s 0, then we simply return what we currently have in cache, no guarantee; - if set to non zero, then the result is at least as fresh as given rv.

    • Optional timeoutSeconds: undefined | number

      Timeout for the list/watch call. This limits the duration of the call, regardless of any activity or inactivity.

    • Optional watch: undefined | false | true

      Watch for changes to the described resources and return them as a stream of add, update, and remove notifications. Specify resourceVersion.

    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

    Returns Promise<object>

    list or watch objects of kind PodTemplate

    Parameters

    • Optional allowWatchBookmarks: undefined | false | true

      allowWatchBookmarks requests watch events with type &quot;BOOKMARK&quot;. Servers that do not implement bookmarks may ignore this flag and bookmarks are sent at the server&#39;s discretion. Clients should not assume bookmarks are returned at any specific interval, nor may they assume the server will send any BOOKMARK event during a session. If this is not a watch, this field is ignored. If the feature gate WatchBookmarks is not enabled in apiserver, this field is ignored. This field is alpha and can be changed or removed without notice.

    • Optional _continue: undefined | string

      The continue option should be set when retrieving more results from the server. Since this value is server defined, clients may only use the continue value from a previous query result with identical query parameters (except for the value of continue) and the server may reject a continue value it does not recognize. If the specified continue value is no longer valid whether due to expiration (generally five to fifteen minutes) or a configuration change on the server, the server will respond with a 410 ResourceExpired error together with a continue token. If the client needs a consistent list, it must restart their list without the continue field. Otherwise, the client may send another list request with the token received with the 410 error, the server will respond with a list starting from the next key, but from the latest snapshot, which is inconsistent from the previous list results - objects that are created, modified, or deleted after the first list request will be included in the response, as long as their keys are after the &quot;next key&quot;. This field is not supported when watch is true. Clients may start a watch from the last resourceVersion value returned by the server and not miss any modifications.

    • Optional fieldSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their fields. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional labelSelector: undefined | string

      A selector to restrict the list of returned objects by their labels. Defaults to everything.

    • Optional limit: undefined | number

      limit is a maximum number of responses to return for a list call. If more items exist, the server will set the `continue` field on the list metadata to a value that can be used with the same initial query to retrieve the next set of results. Setting a limit may return fewer than the requested amount of items (up to zero items) in the event all requested objects are filtered out and clients should only use the presence of the continue field to determine whether more results are available. Servers may choose not to support the limit argument and will return all of the available results. If limit is specified and the continue field is empty, clients may assume that no more results are available. This field is not supported if watch is true. This field is required for apply requests (application/apply-patch) but optional for non-apply patch types (JsonPatch, MergePatch, StrategicMergePatch).

    • Optional force: undefined | false | true

      Force is going to &quot;force&quot; Apply requests. It means user will re-acquire conflicting fields owned by other people. Force flag must be unset for non-apply patch requests.

  • patchNodeStatus(name: string, body: object, pretty?: undefined | string, dryRun?: undefined | string, fieldManager?: undefined | string, force?: undefined | false | true, options?: object): Promise<object>
    • Defined in api/coreV1Api.ts:14645

    partially update status of the specified Node

    Parameters

    • name: string

      name of the Node

    • body: object
    • Optional pretty: undefined | string

      If &#39;true&#39;, then the output is pretty printed.

    • Optional dryRun: undefined | string

      When present, indicates that modifications should not be persisted. An invalid or unrecognized dryRun directive will result in an error response and no further processing of the request. Valid values are: - All: all dry run stages will be processed

    • Optional fieldManager: undefined | string

      fieldManager is a name associated with the actor or entity that is making these changes. The value must be less than or 128 characters long, and only contain printable characters, as defined by https://golang.org/pkg/unicode/#IsPrint. This field is required for apply requests (application/apply-patch) but optional for non-apply patch types (JsonPatch, MergePatch, StrategicMergePatch).

    • Optional force: undefined | false | true

      Force is going to &quot;force&quot; Apply requests. It means user will re-acquire conflicting fields owned by other people. Force flag must be unset for non-apply patch requests.

    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

    Returns Promise<object>

readNamespacedPodLog

  • readNamespacedPodLog(name: string, namespace: string, container?: undefined | string, follow?: undefined | false | true, limitBytes?: undefined | number, pretty?: undefined | string, previous?: undefined | false | true, sinceSeconds?: undefined | number, tailLines?: undefined | number, timestamps?: undefined | false | true, options?: object): Promise<object>
    • Defined in api/coreV1Api.ts:15822

    read log of the specified Pod

    Parameters

    • name: string

      name of the Pod

    • namespace: string

      object name and auth scope, such as for teams and projects

    • Optional container: undefined | string

      The container for which to stream logs. Defaults to only container if there is one container in the pod.

    • Optional follow: undefined | false | true

      Follow the log stream of the pod. Defaults to false.

    • Optional limitBytes: undefined | number

      If set, the number of bytes to read from the server before terminating the log output. This may not display a complete final line of logging, and may return slightly more or slightly less than the specified limit.

    • Optional pretty: undefined | string

      If &#39;true&#39;, then the output is pretty printed.

    • Optional previous: undefined | false | true

      Return previous terminated container logs. Defaults to false.

    • Optional sinceSeconds: undefined | number

      A relative time in seconds before the current time from which to show logs. If this value precedes the time a pod was started, only logs since the pod start will be returned. If this value is in the future, no logs will be returned. Only one of sinceSeconds or sinceTime may be specified.

    • Optional tailLines: undefined | number

      If set, the number of lines from the end of the logs to show. If not specified, logs are shown from the creation of the container or sinceSeconds or sinceTime

    • Optional timestamps: undefined | false | true

      If true, add an RFC3339 or RFC3339Nano timestamp at the beginning of every line of log output. Defaults to false.

    • Default value options: object = {headers: {}}
      • headers: object
        • [name: string]: string

    Returns Promise<object>
